</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umaeghanttuskbone.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maeghant Tuskbone</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 432<br> <font color=#E9D756>(8/4/01 11:14:34 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Kael Enhancement</span><hr size=1> <br>
  Pointless bickering aside, there are some rather interesting questions regarding pets that haven't even been asked.<br>
<br>
  Firstly, I wonder how the change to pet taunt came about.  There was a patch, pets began to taunt greatly, and then a subsequent patch stating that the &quot;Bug where an NPC unerringly sticks to a pet&quot; had been fixed.  So, we have an official statement by VI that pet taunt was bugged, but a later assurance that it was fixed.  For the most part, unless you looked closely, pet taunt before and after the &quot;fix&quot; remained the same.  Essentially, it remained unchanged, at least in application.<br>
<br>
  The change to pet taunt, whatever made it so great, could have either been 1) A mistake or 2) Intentional.<br>
<br>
  If it was a mistake, it has been notoriously difficult to track down and fix.  Ok, I know that VI isn't perhaps the most brilliant assimilation of programmers around, but something as simple as code PRE-Bug and code POST-Bug should be easily examined to correct a &quot;bug&quot; in my opinion.  Which leads me to believe that perhaps 2) is the correct scenario.<br>
<br>
  An intentional increase in pet taunt.  Why?  Did players perhaps ask for this?  Or was this actually a hidden nerf?  Did VI have a set of scenarios in mind which allowed pets to dmg NPCs with virtually no risk to themselves and VI sought to correct this &quot;imbalance&quot;?  Personally, I can easily create a handfull of scenarios which VI may have no official policy against yet found distastefull regarding pets that do not taunt, regardless of the amount of dmg they inflict upon an NPC.  So, in essence, I believe that VI increased pet taunt to combat certain percieved imbalances in the game.<br>
<br>
  Now, with increased pet taunt, a handfull of additionally perhaps game imbalancing strategies have been allowed to exist.  Pets can taunt, pets can tank, pets can recieve CHs.  This is an advantage.  I do not believe that anyone would be so brave as to claim that pets are -not- an advantage.  Whether it be a necro pet, a mage epic pet, or a mob pet, it is to my advantage that it be there... whether it tanks or not.<br>
<br>
  The quite possibly valid argument against excessive pet taunt is that it makes the &quot;big&quot; encounters trivial and, to an extent, I will not argue.  Dain isn't supposed to die to a group of 6, Tormax to 12 (exaggerated values, of course, to illustrate the point).<br>
<br>
  If far far too few people are killing far far too uber mobs, then there is a problem.  If the pet is taunting a greater amount than it's DMG Output plus the hate generated by, &quot;Taunting attacker master,&quot; then there is a problem.<br>
<br>
  Maybe when a pet taunts currently, 5000 hate is added instead of 500, who knows.  This would be a bug.  Or maybe, pet melee output is significantly greater than the average melee's ability to produce hate, therefor the pet tanks.  Ask Enki, he knows alot about this from posts of his I have read and seeing him in action.  This wouldn't exactly be a bug, although VI may find it troubling.<br>
<br>
  Again, it doesn't strike me as appropriate that a pet with double the dmg output of the most hated tank, with taunt on top, would be completely ignored by the mob.  It also doesn't strike me as appropriate that a pet, regardless of dmg output or taunt value, would automatically be tanking.  Why does VI appear to be so completely unable to find the middle ground on this?<br>
<br>
  One thing is clear to me, though.  VI nerfs things which they perceive as too powerfull.  It's the nature of the beast.  CH aggro increased, healing items (Donal's BP) adjusted, Evade reduced in functionality, Charm (complicated... increased in power in an expansion with limited enchanter flexibility and working on strange fixes to decrease it), DB/GB.<br>
<br>
  Looked like I slipped that last one in there on ya, didn't I?  As I understand it, even the illustrious Bane lines have recieved a nerf in the recent past, increasing their recycle times.  I'm sure some people would tell you the nerf was a horrible horrible thing while others would tell you that the Banes were simply too powerfull in their initial form.  How does one supply an argument so powerfull on either side to negate the other?<br>
<br>
  I lack the insight into the game, and I feel each of us as players do, to tell everyone reading this that DB/GB required an increase in casting time.  I lack the insight into the game to inform you all that charming is too damn much!  CHs were evil in original form!  That the Donal's BP nerf was necessssary!  That rogues needed less functionality in Evade!<br>
<br>
  Some people do feel that they have such insight... and more power to them.  I am far too schizophrenic and flexible to buy into any single, generally derivitive, line of argumentation in either support or against nerfs.  Reading the FoH board, I see Furor making a broad statement regarding pets making kills too easy... and I'm sure he is correct to some degree.  But he does make the knee jerk reaction.<br>
<br>
  He doesn't ask why is it the way it is, but simply says why it shouldn't be the way it is.  No suggestions, no theoretical discussion on how suggested changes would influence the game as a whole.<br>
<br>
  What is lacking in his post simply strengthens my belief that... 99% of EQ players simply do not have the inherent understanding of the engine, nor the full picture, to make knowledgable statements regarding nerfs.  The 1% that remain both write and play the game, simple as that.  Now, notice... I'm not saying that players have no right to comment or discuss issues.  I am saying that it is my belief that players are incapable of fully understanding why certain things are enhanced and certain things are nerfed.<br>
<br>
  A burn.  To you confused individuals posting nonsensical rhetoric in a pissing match; Stop.  You are embarassing yourselves, both of our guilds, and most of all... you are embarassing me.  DO NOT assume that you even have the slightest inkling of how it feels to live next to the Magis/DK camp in a mix of respect, fear, and hatred for what... TWO solid years.  Whatever vitrolic emotions are being spewed forth by you guys, on both sides, PALES in comparision to the rich depth of emotion, highs and lows, that I've been pleasured with experiencing in my time on Emarr.  This is my egostical method of saying, &quot;Shut up, the lot of you.&quot;<br>
<br>
  And finally, a quick comment on Kael itself.  Nothing see's invis now, surely that cannot be correct.  Attempt to stop one thing and implement the tools for another.  This is the game we play and every patch it happens again.  Love it or hate it, live it or leave it, it's the nature of the beast.  Those vitrolic manastone arguments from 18 months ago?  Gone in the wind, just as I expect this discussion to fade away.<br>
<br>
  And Chuk:  Slowable dragons are uber.  Hehe, sorry... Ok?  I'm sorry.  I'm trying to end this on something of a positive note to reward those who sludge through my drivel and this is all I can come up with.  Seriously, it's benign and probably false.<br>
<br>
  Emarr is a fantastic server.  I almost... practically... retract all my statements earlier asking the question, &quot;Is anyone uber on Emarr anymore?&quot;<br>
<br>
